The Steelers still hold the advantage based on the remaining games on the schedule. However, the Browns have a realistic opportunity to win the division in the head to head game at the end of the season. The Steelers have been on slide since winning their first 11 games...they could realistically finish the season with 5 straight losses.

This is a challenging question, especially with the form of both the Browns and the Steelers lately. There will be a Division Champion, so another outcome is not an option. Both the Bengals and the Ravens are mathematically eliminated from winning the division so they are also forecasted at 0. The Steelers remain the frontrunner by a game. If the Steelers win one of their last two games, they win the Division. It could come as early as this weekend when the Steelers host the Colts, a game they are actually an underdog in at home. The Browns travel to play the hapless New York Jets, a game they are favored in by 9.5. If the Steelers lose and the Browns win, they are tied on record and head into a winner-take-all showdown in Week 17 in Cleveland for the Division title. A win or a tie by the Steelers there would give them the Division; only a win by the Browns (pending the Week 16 outcomes) would give the Browns a division title. The Steelers have lost their last three games, two to opponents under .500. They are in a terrible run of form, the offense has been anemic, and their defense has been plagued by injuries. However, they have one of the top coaches in the NFL in Mike Tomlin, so if there is a presence that can get them refocused to win one of the last two games, it would be him. The Browns are playing some exciting football and have won 5 of their last 6 games (with their lone loss coming at a last second FG to the Ravens). They are in fantastic form and are hungry for their first playoff birth in years. At this point, I cannot see the Steelers beating the Colts. The Browns should take care of the New York Jets, setting up a week 17 showdown. At this point, the Browns would have to be the favorite. However, the Steelers hold "more outs" than the singular path that the Browns have so I have to give the Steelers a higher forecast at this point than the Browns. If it does turn into a Week 17 matchup for the AFC North, the tide will turn significantly in the favor of the Browns.

The Pittsburgh win over Baltimore greatly increases the likelihood of the Steelers winning the division. Short of an injury to their quarterback, the Steelers should continue to have a strong winning percentage with only three moderate probability losses (Baltimore rematch, Buffalo, Indy). It is not improbable that Pittsburgh could finish the season undefeated given their soft remaining schedule. Meanwhile, Baltimore needs to win the Steelers rematch, plus gain 2 wins on Pittsburgh. Not impossible, but certainly unlikely. Cincinnati and Cleveland are flawed teams, although the Bengals have shown offensive potential and if their defensive improves, they could be a contending team in 2021.

They were obliterated by both the Ravens and Steelers when they played and have really only beat a host of the leagues worst teams. They have no shot at the division. Neither do the Bengals.

Two power house teams. The Ravens offense is nearly impossible to stop, and the Steelers continue to have a show stopping defense (that favors the blitz). This will need to be revised after Nov 1st (when the Steelers and Ravens face off).

While the Browns, Ravens, and Steelers all have 4 wins and the Steelers are the only team left undefeated in the division, these early results are skewed. The Browns only loss came against the Ravens where they gave up 38 points and scored only 6. Their 4 wins come against teams with a combined 7 wins through the first 5 weeks. Similarly, while the Steelers haven't lost, they have 4 wins against teams with a total of 3 wins to this point. Meanwhile, the Ravens' only loss comes at the hands of the reigning Superbowl Champions, with all of their other performances being dominant wins with respectable margins of victory. As the season continues, I suspect the differences between these groups will become more apparent.
Kevin Stefanski
